<div id="review_3165334428" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3165334428" />
    <a title="Jim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/695116-jim"><img alt="Jim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1340192527p2/695116.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3165334428?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim" href="/user/show/695116-jim">Jim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9780743572682" href="/book/show/6984040-the-end-of-faith">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=historical">historical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=1audio">1audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=2non-fiction">2non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=self-help">self-help</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3165334428" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13753735346216900793">An excellent set of reasons why we need to kick religion to the curb. There can be no discussion or compromise when people have differing beliefs based on no evidence or rational reason. The Abrahamic religions all believe that they can look forward to an afterlife that is far better than the one they have now if they follow certain arcane rules. Everyone else will burn in Hell. That&apos;s both incredibly rude &amp; really scary when we have the power to destroy all life on the globe. What reason does a</span>
  <span id="freeText13753735346216900793" style="display:none">An excellent set of reasons why we need to kick religion to the curb. There can be no discussion or compromise when people have differing beliefs based on no evidence or rational reason. The Abrahamic religions all believe that they can look forward to an afterlife that is far better than the one they have now if they follow certain arcane rules. Everyone else will burn in Hell. That's both incredibly rude &amp; really scary when we have the power to destroy all life on the globe. What reason does a True Believer have for not causing Armageddon? Worse, the power to cause this is spreading fast as technology gives each of us more power. As he points out, no longer is it a matter for huge nations like the US &amp; USSR. In short order, individuals may have the power.<br /><br />He says it is time to stop respecting religious beliefs &amp; makes a good case for it. It reminds me of the Boston Legal episode (season 3, episode 5 "Whose God Is It Anyway") where Alan Shore (James Spader) defends Jerry for firing a Scientologist. It's hilarious &amp; true, so Alan wins the case, but it also upset a lot of people. You can find numerous articles about it with dead links to the 2 minute clip, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t5T1B5PIqCg&amp;list=PLMNaPH-oNxOfFUPl7yfQ9Pjam4BgsbXb-&amp;index=37&amp;t=0s" rel="nofollow noopener"> but I found t here. </a> I highly recommend watching it. (If the link dies, google "Alan Shore Enough of this Freedom of Religion Crap".)<br /><br />Harris' argument early on is very similar to Clifford's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28204144.The_Ethics_of_Belief" title="The Ethics of Belief by William Kingdon Clifford" rel="nofollow noopener">The Ethics of Belief</a>, a short book that I gave a 5 star review <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3104287019" rel="nofollow noopener"> here</a> &amp; I recommend reading first. Harris provides more examples of passages from both the Koran &amp; the Bible as to just how misguided, mean-spirited, &amp; ridiculous those books are. He also shows that the Muslim world is about 500 years behind the Christians in their religious practice. That's scary &amp; truly horrifying when one thinks about the Reformation genocides &amp; the Inquisition. Muslims regularly practice killing women &amp; girls for the 'crime' of being raped &amp; then call the murderer a just man. Mothers encourage sons to suicide while killing many innocents. Makes perfect sense. By her religious beliefs, his death leads him to a better life which also assures her 'salvation' since he not only gets a bevvy of virgins, but has 70 open invitations to 'Paradise'. Surely she'll top his list, right? It's pretty obvious that there can be no peace in the Middle East or so many other places while people lend credence to such idiocies.<br /><br />I found some of this repetitive. His lists of religious passages were horrific, but went on too long. I get it! What I didn't hear enough of was how we transfer these beliefs to political ideologies. Maybe that was beyond the scope of this book, but the enthusiasm of the Nazis doesn't seem much different than what our current extremist Left &amp; Right display in the US political arena today. The anti-GMO &amp; anti-vax campaigns are similarly mired in unfounded, fanatic beliefs<br /><br />The "Experiments in Consciousness" chapter was not particularly elucidating. A GR friend recently quoted <i>"There is a God shaped hole in each of us."</i> which is a slightly mangled quote of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/10994.Blaise_Pascal" title="Blaise Pascal" rel="nofollow noopener">Blaise Pascal</a>, who also encouraged lip service to a deity with his <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/pascal-wager/" rel="nofollow noopener"> wager,</a> the height of hypocrisy. I dislike the former, too. There is often a void between our minds &amp; the world, but it is not "God" shaped. It should be filled with spirituality, which is what Harris is aiming at in this chapter, not the unlikely proposition of "God", an indefinable noun that is loaded with monotheistic pretensions by the use of the singular &amp; a capital letter. Too many people do believe it &amp; it's one of the reasons for constant strife &amp; barbarism since it presupposes to know The TRUTH without any basis in evidence or fact.<br /><br />At the end of this edition, Harris has a response to controversy. Folks who believe in religion obviously can't comprehend what he wrote which is as sad as it is amazing. Thanks to a GR friend, I was reminded that his <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/51299.Letter_to_a_Christian_Nation" title="Letter to a Christian Nation by Sam Harris" rel="nofollow noopener">Letter to a Christian Nation</a> is an expanded version of this afterword. I read it first &amp; gave it a <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1091587555" rel="nofollow noopener"> 4 star review here.</a> Like this book, it doesn't quite make 5 stars because it is only acceptable reading for those who are like-minded, such as myself. Religious people obviously can't examine their basic beliefs closely &amp; rationally or they wouldn't be religious.<br /><br />Well narrated &amp; well suited to audio, although the narrator insisted on reading all Harris' examples sanctifying Abrahamic horrific behavior. They were easy enough to skip through, though. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13753735346216900793" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


