<div id="review_11593802" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/11593802" />
    <a title="Eric" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/740329-eric"><img alt="Eric" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1199418994p2/740329.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/11593802?book_show_action=true">Jan 03, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric" href="/user/show/740329-eric">Eric</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer11593802" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3077647498568301593">I&apos;ve been reading this book forever now. I imagine I&apos;ll finish sometime.<br/><br/>I&apos;m sympathetic to Harris&apos; arguments: I&apos;ve been an atheist since I was a teenager. But Harris&apos; book is hypocritical, shallow, and unpleasant. Religion is bad--unless it&apos;s his own brand of Buddhism, apparently. And his defense of torture could not have been easy to write with his head shoved so far up his own asshole. And the sad truth is that however much his general case might apply to almost all religion (potentially even </span>
  <span id="freeText3077647498568301593" style="display:none">I've been reading this book forever now. I imagine I'll finish sometime.<br /><br />I'm sympathetic to Harris' arguments: I've been an atheist since I was a teenager. But Harris' book is hypocritical, shallow, and unpleasant. Religion is bad--unless it's his own brand of Buddhism, apparently. And his defense of torture could not have been easy to write with his head shoved so far up his own asshole. And the sad truth is that however much his general case might apply to almost all religion (potentially even his own), much of the book is merely a thinly-veiled assault on Islam; a reasoned attack on religious superstition in all its forms is one thing--rank bigotry is something else.<br /><br />It's unfortunate: this could have been a great book. There are times that Harris is clever, brilliant and insightful. In fact, I originally purchased this book on the strength of an excerpt that Harris made available online. Had Harris done what he claims to be attempting--illustrating the dangers of medieval superstition in a nuclear age--the book could have been a serviceable defense of capital-R Reason. Instead, we get a bigoted, embarrassing diatribe. Thanks for the help, Sam.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3077647498568301593" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


