  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_335074947" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/335074947" />
    <a title="Scott Rhee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5717792-scott-rhee"><img alt="Scott Rhee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408223108p2/5717792.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/335074947?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott Rhee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott Rhee" href="/user/show/5717792-scott-rhee">Scott Rhee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5717792-scott-rhee?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5717792-scott-rhee?shelf=sociology">sociology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5717792-scott-rhee?shelf=atheism">atheism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer335074947" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9118416490121825104">I am a huge &quot;X-Files&quot; fan. I think what I liked most about the TV show was the relationship between the two main protagonists, FBI agents Dana Scully and Fox Mulder. Scully is a rational-minded skeptic who believes in science and has very little patience for the unexplained. Mulder, however, is a conspiracy theorist who tends to go on faith (in regards to things like Bigfoot, UFOs, and the Bermuda Triangle) and absolutely LOVES anything unexplained. His philosophy is perhaps best summed up by th</span>
  <span id="freeText9118416490121825104" style="display:none">I am a huge "X-Files" fan. I think what I liked most about the TV show was the relationship between the two main protagonists, FBI agents Dana Scully and Fox Mulder. Scully is a rational-minded skeptic who believes in science and has very little patience for the unexplained. Mulder, however, is a conspiracy theorist who tends to go on faith (in regards to things like Bigfoot, UFOs, and the Bermuda Triangle) and absolutely LOVES anything unexplained. His philosophy is perhaps best summed up by the now-iconic poster displayed in his office of a UFO hovering over a field and, above that, the words "I want to believe". Through the course of the series, Scully and Mulder would often engage in some thought-provoking, heated arguments. Ultimately, however, they learned to not only appreciate each other's different worldviews but actually fell in love because of them, illustrating the possibility of a beneficial marriage between science and faith. <br /><br />If only life were that easy.<br /><br />Sam Harris, a philosopher who has extensively studied Eastern and Western religions and who is also a neuroscientist, gracefully tackles the politically-incorrect and (for many) contemptible concept that all religion, and the blind Faith that goes along with it, is not only irrational but dangerous and counter-productive to a society's well-being in his book "The End of Faith". Harris, perhaps, would not necessarily appreciate the Scully-Mulder love story. He does, however, make a pretty compelling case against faith. Just to be clear, too, Harris separates faith into two distinct types: 1) Faith as "a positive attitude in the face of uncertainty (p. 232)", which is the kind of faith that enables many of us to wake up in the morning, drive to work, or gain the courage to ask that cute girl out on a date. This kind of faith is not problematic to Harris. However, 2) Faith as "the belief in historical and metaphysical propositions without sufficient evidence (p. 232)" is extremely problematic, according to Harris, because it is inherently irrational and excludes any attempt to criticize it.<br /><br />Take the Bible (or the Koran), for example. Harris argues that the authority given to these texts are based on flimsy (at best) arguments of their divine origins and are, more often than not, circular arguments. ("The Bible is right because God wrote it, and I know God wrote it because it says so in the Bible...") Of course, try telling this to a Fundamentalist Christian and witness (more often than not) the vitriol and disgust at your audacity at questioning the Bible's authority. In less-sane eras, people who questioned the Bible in any way were thrown into prison, tortured, or worse. Harris argues (rightly) that times haven't changed that much, and in many parts of the world, state-sanctioned torture and murder are still de rigueur, especially in many Islamist countries, for the crime of questioning the Koran or Muhammed's teachings.<br /><br />Harris doesn't discount the beauty of a "spiritual" life, nor does he necessarily advocate for atheism or the destruction of all religions, but he does advocate for rationality in existing religions. "[A] certain range of human experience can be appropriately described as "spiritual" or "mystical"---experiences of meaningfulness, selflessness, and heightened emotion that surpass our narrow identities as "selves" and escape our current understanding of the mind and brain. But nothing about these experiences justifies arrogant and exclusionary claims about the unique sanctity of any text. There is no reason that our ability to sustain ourselves emotionally and spiritually cannot evolve with technology, politics, and the rest of culture. Indeed, it must evolve, if we are to have any future at all. (pps. 39-40)"<br /><br />The thoroughness and precision with which Harris shapes his argument is impressive. In concise laymen's terms (along with copious and detailed endnotes that literally take up a third of the book), Harris covers the nature of belief, the history of religious atrocities in the Western world, the dangers of Islam (both radical and non), the philosophical arguments of Pragmatism versus Realism, and a scientific approach to the concepts of good and evil. At the very least, his book is fascinating. At most, it is a logical, intellectual call to arms against fundamentalism, in any religion, that advocates violence in the name of God. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9118416490121825104" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


